Sentiment analysis with Naive Bayes Vs LSTM keras model

Introduction ¶

In this project we will compare two methods of sentiment analysis:

  • The prediction of Negative/Positive using a simple Naïve Bayes model
  • The prediction of Negative/Positive using a LSTM kera model

    • The dataset is twitter post with label : 'neutral', 'negative', 'positive'
    in this project, we will do many functions handy to understand how they work

    Removing the punctuation¶

    In [11]:
    def process_string(X):
    ################ Remove punctuation####################
     # use this string as separation between X elements
    sep='28487612184'
    # converting X array to one string 
    s=str(sep).join(X)
    # use the punctuation collected above
    punctuation='''\xa0Â\t<¯]&*`)¿_|$;Ã?}½{´.@+\\-¡%>#\x82/^(:![=~',"'''
    #remove punctuation
    out = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(punctuation), ' ', s)
    ############## Lower the text ##########################
    out=out.lower()
    ############## Remove multiple space ##################
    out=re.sub(' +', ' ', out)
    ############# convert out to array and remove begenning and end space of each elements
    #convert out to array
    out=np.array(out.split(sep)).astype(str)
    # removing the begen and the end space of each elements
    out = np.char.strip(out)
    return out

    Preparing train set and validation set¶

    In general, we split the available data to:


    * Train set: used to train the models
    * Developpement set : used to tune the models
    * Test set: use to validate the model after tuning, In the actual project we will call it Validation set to use just "t" for train and "v" for validation

    In the actual example, we will split data to only train/validation set

    GloVe: Global Vectors for Word Representation¶

    The idea is to code each word of english with a velcor of n elements, in the actual example n=50 and the dictionnary has 400k words


    You can download the glove.6B.50d.txt dictionnary at the link
    https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/watts2/glove6b50dtxt

    We can use Word2vec intead of GloVe, below the differnece between theme that we can found in internet: her


    Glove model is based on leveraging global word to word co-occurance counts leveraging the entire corpus. Word2vec on the other hand leverages co-occurance within local context (neighbouring words)
    In [41]:
    file=r"C:\Users\a037702\OneDrive - Alliance\00_DATA_SCIENCE\10_personnel\01_sentiment_anal_data\glove.6B.50d.txt"
def read_glov(file):
    df = pd.read_csv(file, sep=" ", quoting=3, header=None, index_col=0)
    Glove= {key: val.values for key, val in df.T.items()}
    return Glove
Glove= read_glov(file)

    Naive Bayes classifier ¶

    wiki definition¶


    In statistics, naive Bayes classifiers are a family of simple "probabilistic classifiers" based on applying Bayes' theorem with strong (naive) independence assumptions between the features (see Bayes classifier). They are among the simplest Bayesian network models,[1] but coupled with kernel density estimation, they can achieve high accuracy levels.

    For more information see wikipedia link:

    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier

    The Naive Bytes class¶

    Below the class of Naive Bayes classifier, the class functions will be explained one by one after the class code

    In [123]:
    class NaiveBytes():
    def __init__(self):
        self.logprior=None
        self.list_rem='''! ( ) - [ ] { } ; : ' " \ , < > . / ? @ # $ % ^ & * _ ~ ' " '''
        self.list_rem=self.list_rem.split(' ')
        self.lambd=None
    def print_progress_bar(self,index, total, label):
        n_bar = 50  # Progress bar width
        progress = index / total
        sys.stdout.write('\r')
        sys.stdout.write(f"[{'=' * int(n_bar * progress):{n_bar}s}] {int(100 * progress)}%  {label}")
        sys.stdout.flush()
    def freq_dic(self,X,Y):
        dic={}
        N=len(X)
        for i in range(len(X)):
            x=X[i]
            y=Y[i]
            for w in x.split(' '): 
                wl=w.lower()
                if wl not in self.list_rem:
                    try: 
                        dic[wl][y+1]+=1 
                    except: 
                        dic[wl]=[0,0,0]
                        dic[wl][y+1]+=1 
            if int(100*(i-1)/N)+1==int(100*i/N):
                self.print_progress_bar(i, N, "prograss: "+str(i)+'/'+str(N))
        return dic
    def logprior_cal(self,Y):
        D_pos=(Y==1).astype('int').sum()
        D_neg=(Y==-1).astype('int').sum()
        logprior=np.log(D_pos/D_neg)
        return logprior
    def fit(self,X,Y):
        print('input processing')
        xx=[x.split(' ') for x in X]
        print('parameter calculation')
        dic=self.freq_dic(X,Y)
        dfdic=pd.DataFrame(dic.values(),index=dic.keys(),columns=['neg','neutr','pos'])
        dfdic['logpos']=np.log((dfdic.pos+1)/(dfdic.pos.sum()+len(dfdic)))
        dfdic['logneg']=np.log((dfdic.neg+1)/(dfdic.neg.sum()+len(dfdic)))
        dfdic['lambda']=dfdic['logpos']-dfdic['logneg']
        self.logprior=self.logprior_cal(Y)
        self.lambd=dfdic['lambda'].to_dict()
        del(dfdic)
    def score_cal(self,X):
        SCORE=[]
        N=len(X)
        for i in range(len(X)):
            x=X[i]
            score=0
            for w in x.split(' '):
                wl=w.lower()
                try: 
                    score+=self.lambd[wl]
                except : pass
            score+=self.logprior
            SCORE.append(score)
            if int(100*(i-1)/N)+1==int(100*i/N):
                self.print_progress_bar(i, N, "prograss: "+str(i)+'/'+str(N))
        return np.array(SCORE) 
    def predict(self,X,without_neutral=True):
        if self.lambd is None: 
            print('error, fit model OR read parameters before prediction')
            return None 
        else: 
            if without_neutral:
                Y_hat=self.score_cal(X)
                Y_hat=(Y_hat>0).astype('int8')
                return Y_hat*2-1
            else: 
                print('to be completed in the future')
                return None 
    def accuracy(self,Y,Y_hat):
        arr_acc=((Y-Y_hat )==0).astype('int8')
        acc=arr_acc.sum()/len(arr_acc)
        return acc,arr_acc
    def save_params(self,filename):
        np.savez_compressed(filename,lambd=self.lambd,logprior=self.logprior)
    def read_paras(self,filename):
        loaded = np.load(filename,allow_pickle=True)
        self.lambd=loaded['lambd'].tolist()   # tolist to extract value
        self.logprior=loaded['logprior'].tolist()

    LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory) ¶

    In this secotion, we will predict sentiment by LSTM RNN (Long Short-Term Memory), below a defenition of LSTM from Wikipedia

    "Long short-term memory (LSTM) is an artificial neural network used in the fields of artificial intelligence and deep learning. Unlike standard feedforward neural networks, LSTM has feedback connections. Such a recurrent neural network (RNN) can process not only single data points (such as images), but also entire sequences of data (such as speech or video). This characteristic makes LSTM networks ideal for processing and predicting data. For example, LSTM is applicable to tasks such as unsegmented, connected handwriting recognition, speech recognition, machine translation, speech activity detection, robot control, video games, and healthcare."


    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_short-term_memory

    MaxLenght function¶

    Is a function that calculate the maximum number of word in a sentence from an input as array

    In [14]:
    def maxLen(Xp):
    m=0
    for x in Xp:
        m=np.max((len(x.split(' ')),m))
    return m

    Below max number of word in a sentence in training set is 34

    In [6]:
    maxLen(Xtpn)
    Out[6]:
    34

    The embedding funciton of the inputs¶

    The embeding is an operation that replace a text by vectors. if we have a sentence as "i love python", and e1, e2, e3 are the vectros of words 'i/love/python' in the GloVe dictonary, and the maximum number of words for each sentence is 5 for example. The embedding matrix of this sentence will be [e1,e2,e2,e0,e0], where e0 are zeros vectors to complet the number 5 br>
    In the actual project, we start with zeros verctors like: [e0,e0,e1,e2,e2]

    In the general case, we use an embedding layer that convert index of words to vectors input, but in the below example, we decided to make the function manually to understand this operation.

    In [16]:
    def embedding_input(Xp,maxlen=None):
    # calculate the maximum number of word in sentences array 
    if maxlen is None:
        maxlen=maxLen(Xp)
    # m is the number of rows in input array 
    m=len(Xp)
    # calculate the dimension of each word vector: actually n=50 for the glove.6b.50d.txt 
    n=Glove['i'].shape[0]
    # initialize the output matrix by zeros
    Xvec=np.zeros((m,maxlen,n))
    # loop through each sentence in the input array
    for i in range(len(Xp)):
        # splite each sentence words: separator = space
        sent=Xp[i].split(' ')
        Lsent=len(sent)
        for j in range(Lsent):
            w=sent[j]
            # j+(maxlen-Lsent): is used to left 0 in the left side (not the right side)
            a=Xvec[i,j+(maxlen-Lsent),:]
            try:# try if the word is in Glove
                Xvec[i,j+(maxlen-Lsent),:]=Glove[w].tolist()
            except:
                pass
    return Xvec

    The output is a 2D array with word index


    for more information , see the official [link](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/preprocessing/text/Tokenizer)
    ***The official definition of the Tokenizer***: This class allows to vectorize a text corpus, by turning each text into either a sequence of integers (each integer being the index of a token in a dictionary) or into a vector where the coefficient for each token could be binary, based on word count, based on tf-idf...
    By default, all punctuation is removed, turning the texts into space-separated sequences of words (words may include the ' character). These sequences are then split into lists of tokens. They will then be indexed or vectorized.

    During the model building, we must add an Embedding layer by the below code
    model.add(Embedding(max_fatures, embed_dim,input_length = X_sequ.shape[1]))


    This layer convert each index with the corresponding vector

    The Kera Neural network model¶

    In [47]:
    def MODEL(input_shape,output_shape):
    # input layer
    inp= Input(shape=input_shape ,dtype='float32')
    
    # LSTM layer with 128-dimensional hidden state
    X = LSTM(units = 128, return_sequences= True)(inp)
    # dropout with a probability of 0.5
    X = Dropout(rate=0.5)(X)
    
    # Propagate X trough another LSTM layer with 128-dimensional hidden state
    X = LSTM(units = 128, return_sequences= False)(X)
    # dropout with a probability of 0.5
    X = Dropout(rate=0.5)(X)
    
    # Propagate X through a Dense layer with softmax activation to get back a batch of 5-dimensional vectors.
    X = Dense(output_shape)(X)
    # Add a softmax activation
    X = Activation('softmax')(X)
    
    # Create Model instance which converts sentence_indices into X.
    model = Model(inputs=inp, outputs=X)
    return model

    We can also use the below method to define the model
    from keras.models import Sequential
    input_shape=Xt_emb.shape[1:]
    output_shape=Yt_oh.shape[1]

    model2 = Sequential()
    model2.add(Input(shape=input_shape ,dtype='float32'))
    model2.add(LSTM(units = 128, return_sequences= True))
    model2.add(Dropout(rate=0.5))
    model2.add(LSTM(units = 128, return_sequences= False))
    model2.add(Dropout(rate=0.5))
    model2.add(Dense(output_shape,'softmax'))

    The One Hot encoding function¶

    The below function encode the output with the one Hot methode.
    Example: y=['A','B','C','A'] => One_Hot(y)=[[1,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,1],[1,0,0]]]

    In the actual project, we propose to do it hundley, otherwise we can use the sklearn function below
    sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder

    In [21]:
    def One_Hot_Encoding(Y):
    unique=np.unique(Y)
    Y2_onhot=np.zeros((len(Y),len(unique)))
    for i,x in enumerate (Y):
        j=np.argwhere(unique==x)[0][0]
        Y2_onhot[i,j]=1
    return Y2_onhot

    Conclusion ¶

    In this project we compared two methods of sentiment analysis:

  • The prediction of Negative/Positive using a simple Naïve Bayes model
  • The prediction of Negative/Positive using a LSTM kera model

    • Below a table that resume the accuracy for both models
    Naive Bayes LSTM
    Train set accurancy 0.936 0.994
    Test/val set accurancy 0.867 0.864

    We notice that for the actual exemple, both model accuracies are close to each others, especially for the test set accuracy.
    For the LSTM model, we have a bias of 0.006 (low), and a variance of 0.136 (high):

  • Theoretically we can reduce the model with increasing model size, and with increasing the train set
  • The variance in the other hand can be reduced with the increasing of the train set and with more regularization

    • As remark, the naive bayes model is very simple and fast comparing to the LSTM, so it can be a solution for some sample classification task









    Annexe 1: TextBlob ¶

    TextBlob is a Python (2 and 3) library for processing textual data. It provides a simple API for diving into common natural language processing (NLP) tasks such as part-of-speech tagging, noun phrase extraction, sentiment analysis, classification, translation, and more.

    In this project, we will use this library for sentiment analysis.

    For more details for Textblob, please see the below link


    https://textblob.readthedocs.io/en/dev/
    https://pypi.org/project/textblob/
    In [66]:
    from textblob import TextBlob
